0.header:
A burn can be minor or it may be a life threatening emergency.

Let's determine the type of burn you are looking at before we send you to a pharmacist for an over-the-counter recommendation or the nearest emergency room.

1.header: Was this burn caused by a chemical?

2.header:
Seek urgent care or emergency room.

Here is why:

  • The chemical is still reacting with your skin.

3.header: Was it caused by electricity?

4.header:
Seek urgent care or emergency room.

Here is why:

  • Worse than you think.

5.header: Did you inhale smoke with this burn?

6.header:
Seek urgent care or emergency room.

Here is why:

  • Need complete medical evaluation.

7.header: Is the burn forming blisters?

9.header: Is the affected area about or larger than the size of your palm?

10.header:
Seek urgent care or emergency room.

Here is why:

  • Need complete evaluation

11.header: Does the burn look whitish?

13.header: Does it look blackened or charred?

15.header: Does it look deep into the tissues?

16.header:
Seek urgent care emergency room.

Here is why:

  • Sign of a third degree burn.

17.header: Does the burn area feel numb to your touch?

18.header:
Seek urgent care or emergency room.

Here is why:

  • Possible third degree burn.

19.header:
Would you say you are not sure how serious it is...

...but it looks pretty bad?

20.header:
Seek urgent care or emergency room.

Here is why:

  • Don't tough it out.
  • It is going to get worse.

21.header:
Are there other symptoms with this burn?

Symptoms such as cuts, bleeding, headache, broken anything?

22.header:
Seek urgent care or emergency room.

Here is why:

  • Things are worse than you think.

23.header:
Those were to rule out going to the emergency room.

Now, let's see if it is something you can take care of yourself if you are convinced it does not require a visit to the emergency room.

30.header:
Meanwhile, run cool tap water on the burn area as soon as possible.

You need to do this for an average of 20 minutes. This will take heat away from the affected area and reduce swelling.

You can do that while using this app to help you decide on the best course of action to take.

Do not apply ice or iced water to the burn. This may cause the blood vessels in the area to constrict and lead to the death of tissues surrounding the burn area or frostbite.

31.header:
Is the burn area larger than 3 inches in diameter?

And you think this is a second degree burn?

32.header:
Seek urgent care or emergency room.

Here is why:

  • The skin surface area is too large for self-care measures.
  • Second degree burns in an area larger than 3 inches in diameter require urgent medical care.

33.header: Is the burn area bleeding?

34.header:
Seek urgent care or emergency room.

Here is why:

  • You can't stop the bleeding yourself. Don't even waste your time trying.

35.header: Is the affected area swelling or very swollen?

36.header:
Seek urgent care or emergency room.

Here is why:

  • Need to prevent or treat infection.

37.header:
Is the burn area patchy white-to-red?

And very painful?

38.header:
Seek urgent care or emergency room.

Here is why:

  • Looking at second degree burn or partial thickness burn.

39.header: Is the affected area on the face?

40.header:
Seek urgent care or emergency room.

Here is why:

  • You don't want to risk scarring.

41.header: Is it on the groin?

43.header: Is the burn on the feet?

44.header:
Seek urgent care or emergency room.

Here is why:

  • There is a high chance it would get infected
  • It is going to swell up pretty bad.

45.header: Is this burn on a major joint?

46.header:
Seek urgent care or emergency room.

Here is why:

  • Joint movement would make it difficult to heal.
  • Need professional dressing.

47.header:
Are you diabetic or immune compromised?

Or elderly?

48.header:
Seek urgent care or emergency room.

Here is why:

  • Don't even think about self care.

49.header: Now, did you have this burn about 2 days ago and you are still feeling pain?

51.header:
Was this burn a few days ago and the area is still red?

Still swollen?

52.header:
Seek urgent care or call your doctor.

Here is why:

  • Looking at signs of infection.

53.header:
Was this burn a few days ago and the area is draining?

Forming pus?

54.header:
Seek urgent care or call your doctor.

Here is why:

  • Looking at infection.

55.header: Did this burn occur a few days ago and you are feeling feverish?

56.header:
Seek urgent care or call your doctor.

Here is why:

  • May be looking at a possible infection that your body is fighting.

57.header: Finally, was this burn a few days ago and now you are seeing red streaks spreading from the burn?

58.header:
Seek urgent care or call your doctor.

Here is why:

  • Signs of a possible infection.

59.header:
We tried to rule out second degree burns that require urgent care.

You may be looking at First degree burn if none of the questions have applied to you so far.

But let's be sure it is what you are looking at.

60.header:
In the case of a first degree burn, only the outer layer of skin called the epidermis is affected.

This outer layer hasn't been burned through. If this is the case, you can take care of it with selfcare.
Let's continue and see what we've got.

61.header: If it just happened, is the area red and swollen a bit?

63.header: Once again any blistering?

65.header: It should be dry and painful. Is it?

66.header:
Seek urgent care or emergency room.

Here is why:

  • Remember, if you are not sure how serious it is, go to the nearest urgent care clinic or emergency room.

67.header: Can you dress it up yourself or do you have someone to help you do it?

68.header:
Seek urgent care or emergency room.

Here is why:

  • These are the places that will dress up the wound for you professionally.

69.header:
Alright, let's see what to use over the counter for this burn.

Remember, if you are not sure how serious it is, go to the nearest urgent care clinic or emergency room.

The effect of the burn is still going on and it is going to get worse until the skin finish reacting to the burn.

Would you like to see what a pharmacist recommend over-the-counter to take care of this burn or go to the nearest urgent care clinic to you?

53.title: Sunburn
dlg:
The full effect of the sunburn to your skin may not appear for a day or more. By the time the skin starts to become red, the damage has been done.

For example, blisters can develop hours to days later. Meanwhile, stay away from the sun until you have taken care of this.

0.header:
Better to prevent than treat.
Keep this in mind for next time.

Before we begin, if it just happened, soak a towel or t-shirt in cool water, wring out the excess water and place on the sunburned area.

Now, go in front or under a fan or air conditioner to start cooling off as you are using this app to figure out how to take care of this.



It is important to rule out the need for emergency medical care or urgent care.

So let's get started.

1.header: Do you have fever or chills?

2.header:
Seek urgent care or call your doctor.

Here is why:

  • Worse than you are imagining.
  • Know that the effect of the sun burn is ongoing and it would get worse.

3.header: What about a headache in addition to the sunburn?

4.header:
Do you feel faint, dizzy?

Or nauseated?

5.header:
Seek urgent care or call your doctor.

Here is why:

  • Need to rule out possible dehydration.
  • It is going to get worse.

6.header:
Any blisters that are covering a large part of your body?

Very painful?

7.header:
Seek urgent care or call the doctor.

Here is why:

  • May need corticosteroid pills.

8.header: Do you have red streaks along the arm or legs?

9.header:
Seek urgent care or call your doctor.

Here is why:

  • Possible infection.

10.header:
Are you experiencing swelling of the skin?

And is the pain becoming unbearable?

11.header:
Seek urgent care or call your doctor.

Here is why:

  • Need professional evaluation.

12.header: Is your skin red and tender?

14.header: Is your skin warm or painful to touch?

15.header:
No?
You may not be looking at sunburn. If you think otherwise, let's Continue.

16.header:
The effect of the sunburn may still be ongoing.

One more question before we send you to the pharmacist for an over-the-counter recommendation.

20.header: In your estimation, what percentage (%) of your body is sunburned?

21.header:
You said:{{currentTemp}}%

Once sunburn occurs, there is little you can do to limit skin damage.

Now, make sure you:

  • Drink plenty of fluid to prevent dehydration

  • Get a towel, dampen it with cool tap water and apply it to the affected areas

  • Or just take a cool bath or shower if you can.

The sunburned area will be peeling for some days after the sunburn. The pain is worst between 6 and 48 hours after sun exposure.

Let's see what a pharmacist recommend you use over-the-counter.

22.header:
You said:{{currentTemp}}%

Note that:
Symptoms and signs appear in 1 to 24 hours and usually peak within 72 hours except in severe cases.

Skin is going to be peeling on sunburned areas for many days after the sunburn.

The pain is worst between 6 and 48 hours after sun exposure.

Well, let's see what a pharmacist recommend you use over-the-counter for this sunburn or would you like to visit the nearest urgent care clinic to you?

23.header:
You said:{{currentTemp}}%

Pretty much all over?

Symptoms such as fever, chills, weakness and/or shock may develop if a large portion of the body surface is affected. So if at anytime you feel it is getting worse, seek urgent medical care.

Peeled skin may be extremely vulnerable to sunlight for several weeks. Further exposure should be avoided until sunburn has completely subsided.

we strongly recommend you visit the nearest urgent care clinic to you.

You may need steroidal pills for the inflammation. You cannot put over the counter steroid creams to a large skin surface area.

If you don't think so, well, let's see what a pharmacist recommend you use over-the-counter for this sunburn.

54.title: Poison Ivy
dlg:
Note that the rash usually appear about 1 to 2 days after you come in contact with the oil. But it can take upto to 2 weeks for it to appear after touching the plant.

Usually, the first time you get the oil on your skin, the rash might take upto a week to show up. But with later contacts, it develops much more quickly.

0.header:
These plants release an oily resin (urushiol) when bruised.

Contact with the oil usually trigger an allergic reaction on the skin.



Let's see what to use over-the-counter for poison ivy.

1.header:
We will focus on answering the questions listed below.
  1. Is this poison ivy?

  2. Do you need to go to an urgent care clinic for this?

  3. If not, what can you use over-the-counter to take care of this?

2.header: Have you or someone in the household been in the woods the past 2 weeks or so?

4.header: Has your pet been in the woods or brush lately?

5.header:
Yes?
You should start suspecting poison ivy, but not so fast.

Note that poison ivy not only can be acquired through direct contact with the plant, but also indirect contact with let's say your dog that went to fetch something in the woods, tools you used to trim the woods and clothing that have urushiol on them.

6.header:
Looking at the affected area, is it red?

And itchy?

8.header: Are you feeling a burning sensation in the affected area?

10.header: Does the area show blisters with fluid?

12.header: Does it show small bumps or swelling?

13.header:
Yes?
Start suspecting poison ivy.

14.header: Is the area in a pattern like a straight red streak on the arm or leg?

15.header:
Yes?
You are more than likely looking at poison ivy.

Straight red streaking on an arm or leg will result from brushing against poison ivy unknowingly.

Note that if you came in contact with something that has the oil in it, the rash may be more spread out.

16.header: If you think you are looking at poison ivy, let's see if you need to see a doctor.

20.header: Is this poison ivy rash around the eyes?

21.header:
Seek urgent care or call the doctor.

Here is why:

  • It could spread to affect the eye which can be dangerous.

22.header:
Does it affect the mouth?
(..like a swollen mouth)

23.header:
Seek urgent care or call the doctor.

Here is why:

  • Nothing over the counter will take care of this.

24.header: Is a very large area of the body affected?

25.header:
Seek urgent care or call the doctor.

Here is why:

  • Will need steroidal pills or shot for the inflammation.
  • Can't apply over the counter steroidal creams or lotions to a large area.

26.header: Is the poison ivy rash painful?

28.header: Is it warm to touch?

29.header:
Seek urgent care or call the doctor.

Here is why:

  • May be looking at an infection.

30.header: Is the affected area swollen?

32.header:
Have you tried something over-the-counter yet and no relief?

Or the rash is getting worse?

33.header:
Seek urgent care or call the doctor.

Here is why:

  • Will need a prescription anti inflammatory steroid pills to take care of this.

34.header: Did the rash disappear and now it is back?

35.header:
Seek urgent care or call the doctor.

Here is why:

  • Much worse than you think. You body is losing the battle.
